          "body": "The institutional architecture of vv. 8-11 is more sophisticated than it first appears. Jehoshaphat establishes not one court but two: a regional network in the fortified cities (v. 5) and a central appellate body in Jerusalem composed of Levites, priests, and heads of fathers' households (v. 8). The Jerusalem court handles the most complex disputes — 'between blood and blood, between law and commandment, statutes and ordinances' (v. 10) — cases where local courts have reached their limit or where the categories of law themselves are in dispute. The division of labor within the Jerusalem court is also careful: Amariah the chief priest oversees matters pertaining to the LORD; Zebadiah the son of Ishmael oversees matters pertaining to the king (v. 11). This is not a separation of church and state in the modern liberal sense — both spheres are answerable to the LORD — but it is a functional distinction between ecclesiastical law and royal administration. What is most striking is the **warning function** assigned to the judges in v. 10: they are not merely to adjudicate but to warn litigants who are about to incur guilt before the LORD. The judicial office has a prophetic dimension — the judge who sees the law being violated has an obligation to say so before the case is decided, so that guilt does not accumulate and wrath does not fall. Judicial negligence, in this framework, is not a neutral failure; it is itself a sin that incurs guilt."
